I'm grateful that I can still do jobs that matter to me in this
business. The switch to DV and prosumer acceptability has been a mixed
blessing. I'm in South Africa at the moment shooting on my Z1, by
myself for a podcast about a group doing HIV/AIDS work and I love that
I breezed through customs with two bags, but get weary working alone
and knowing that I'm not able to make the best images I'm capable of,
because of the gear, because of the time alloted, because of the
miserable budgets and because not only are people not willing to pay
for better craft, they don't know what it is and don't want to take
even a moment to achieve it.

I continue to make a living and am managing to put my daughters
through college by diversifying, teaching workshops in Maine and
Uganda, teaching at the USC film school, still occasionally shooting
for the BBC or Channel 4 (UK) on the west coast (they can't afford to
fly people around any more, even with the strong pound) picking up
small jobs as they come in. My greatest satisfaction comes from making
a film or two a year for NGOs, usually on development issues, but to
be able to do that, I need to do it all in-house (ie, myself) except
for music composition and After Effects graphics work. Learning and
mastering Final Cut Pro has been probably the smartest thing I've done
since marrying my wife.

I'm living the life I've dreamed of, but it has involved working my
ass off and never stopping. I've had the greatest experiences of
anyone I know, but really can't say that I would recommend this career
any more, mostly due to the difficulty of doing great work and the
continuing decline of television.

I'm 54, shot my first film in 1976 and hope to still be shooting when
I'm 70 and beyond. Yeah, my eyes are failing and I hate it, but I
still manage (yes, the diopter is already at the end, but I seem to
remember it always being so. I haven't been able to work with a
flipout screen for two years.)

Bill Megalos
Venice, CA
billmegalos.com

