I graduated as a cultural anthropologist in 1989, 18 years after I had
entered the university... I had dropped out during my study for many
years, first part time, later completely (when I took up my study again I
had to call the University to ask where the Institute for Cultural
Anthropology had moved to...) Turmoil of life, and got film training. As a
minor at the University I did Film Art, and Visual Ethnography (theory and
film course). After my study I got a research job at the University of
Amsterdam, doing research for the Government on inland navigation (the
subject of my thesis). Then I also got a teaching job there, teaching
visual anthropology. I gave lectures on the theory and history of
documentary, esp. the anthropological films, and also taught the practice
of filmmaking (the students worked on low band U-matic at the time), on
three levels. In the mean time, I also continued to make documentaries and
informational films, esp. later, when the visual anthropology disappeared
from the UvA, due to financial mismanagement of the director of the
faculty at large. Since then I'm living as a street dog, taking a bone
here, a bread there.... Well, doing informational films (either camera, or
sound, or editing, or script and direction, or parts of it, or everything
on my own) and documentaries. Teaching semesters and courses at other
universities.

I have been the director of a documentary film festival during 6 years (up
till three years ago), it took me at least half of all my time, but it was
mainly a labor of love ( www.beeldvoorbeeld.nl ), earning me at max a few
thousand euro a year. The last years I mainly made my money working for a
consultant agency, specialized in the cultural sector and in issues on
multiculturalism. For example: now I'm doing research for a middle-sized
city in the Netherlands, where they want to get ethnic minorities more
involved in cultural affairs. I have to do research, write a masterplan,
and produce two projects as a sort of standard for the future. Apart from
that, I have been working for many years now as a writer and text editior,
mainy in the cultural and non-profit field.

But my main thing at the moment is a documentary I've been wanting to make
already for many years, about inland navigation in Europe. The new
Rhine-Main-Danube canal made it possible to sail from Rotterdam, The
Netherlands, all the way to the Black Sea, and vice versa. This has lots
of historical, political, social, economical and ecological implications.
And it's 'urgent' in the sense that the Danube ends as the border of
Rumania and Bulgary, since Jan 1 member states of the EU, and the delta at
the Black Sea, is Rumanian. And in Serbia, the bridges that were bombed by
the NATO during the Balkan war, have been restored, making naval
transportation easier again. I shot already 50 hours, with a small grant
from a Dutch Broadcaster (the best one we have, I have to say to my
luck...). When they approve this, I'll continue. I have put a lot of my
own money in it, have *very* large debts now, so trying to pay off parts
of it with my consultancy work.

I'm shooting this docu on my own, which is tough, since I'm no longer a
young man... (55 now). Have to travel alone, with Z1, rig, general luggage
etc. Started with too much gear, and doing most of the shooting with just
the camera, the DVRIG PRO and the Sanken CS01 (great mike). Sometimes
additional wireless mike etc. But dropped the DAT for general / additional
sound (it didn't function well, as well). Am considering to sell the Z1
and buy a SOny A1 (bit outdated now) or maybe even one or two consumer
camera's (Canon HV20, Sony HC7).
My main problem though is my RSI - carpal tunnel syndrome, but not as much
at my wrists but shoulders, arms, back; and having a tennis ellbow now
already for a couple of months. That's also the reason I'm considering a
lighter camera.

So, doing things I like, making not money enough at all. But I really want
to make this film, after that we will see...

Best,
Ton Guiking
