<POSTDATE> 2007-08-11T05:06:00 </POSTDATE>
Chiming in from Tokyo...

I'm about to turn 50. In college, married a girl who grew up in
Japan as the daughter of missionaries. Her dad knew a guy running
a little production company and told him about this American kid
his daughter was about to marry. Got a letter out of the blue
offering a two year job to do some photography and script writing
for an English radio program. An overseas job right out of
college ought to look good on a resume, so we went. But I really
clicked with them and with Japan, and they liked my work... so
I've been here ever since.

I went on the TV production crew when my Japanese got good
enough. We're now making a weekly program that airs in 11 'rural'
markets ('rural' for Japan, but they don't have rural the way
Americans understand it!) It's sort of a local color program,
introducing people from all walks of life. Recently we've done
shows on a custom shoe maker, bamboo weaving artisan (don't laugh
-- one of his pieces we shot has a US$20,000+ price tag on it!),
a baker, and then one guy that has about 8 businesses on his name
card -- he has a day care center for kids, an old people's home,
a group home for handicapped, and lawn and garden business to
employ handicapped, and pastors a little church. I thought I was
busy until we shot him! I'm the main cameraman, and do some
editing -- mostly finishing work, color correction, etc. We're
shooting SD, waiting for the local stations we air on to request
HD before we move in that direction.

To some degree language and customs have been problems, but all
in all it has be fascinating to work in another cultural setting,
especially in a job that gets me out to so many different places,
meeting so many different, interesting people.

Okay, that's me.... who's next?

Tim Selander
Tokyo, Japan
